\par
\pard\i Notes: The tables report unweighted descriptive statistics by school. Referral outcomes are expressed as referral frequency per 170 enrolled days so students are compared on a common exposure scale. Standard deviations are shown in parentheses. School-based referrals include Level I through Level IV incidents. Bus referrals include Local/Transportation Level I, Transportation Level II, and Transportation Level III incidents. The difference column is JMTES minus JES.\i0\par
\par
\pard\b\fs28 Discussion\b0\fs24\par
\par
\pard Descriptively, JMTES students had lower school-based referral frequency than JES students. The mean total school referral frequency was 0.27 referrals per 170 enrolled days at JMTES compared with 0.69 at JES, a raw difference of -0.42 referrals per 170 days.\par
\par
\pard The school-level breakdown shows lower average referral frequency at JMTES for Level I, Level II, and Level III referrals. Level IV referrals were rare at both schools, with a small positive raw difference for JMTES because the mean was 0.015 at JMTES and 0.007 at JES.\par
\par
\pard Bus referral frequency was also lower at JMTES in the descriptive comparison. The mean total bus referral frequency was 0.03 referrals per 170 enrolled days at JMTES compared with 0.16 at JES, a difference of -0.13 referrals per 170 days.\par
\par
\pard For bus referral levels, JMTES had lower average Level II referral frequency than JES and very low Level I and Level III bus referral frequencies in both schools. These level-specific descriptive statistics are useful for identifying which types of referrals drive the overall bus referral difference.\par
\par
\pard These referral descriptive statistics are unadjusted and should not be interpreted as causal estimates. They summarize raw school differences before applying overlap weighting, Poisson regression, or covariate adjustment.\par
